Queueing Theory Problems
Problem 1:
A system is being designed. The inter-arrival times of customers are expected to
be exponentially distributed with a mean of 50 msec. Three options are considered:
a- One single-server queue with infinite buffer space. The service time is constant at 20 msec.
b- One two-server queue with infinite buffer space. The service times are exponentially
distributed with a mean of 40 msec at each server.
c- One single-server queue with limited buffer space to 5. The service time is exponentially
distributed with a mean 1/ = 25 msec.
Find the waiting time in each option.

Problem 2:
Consider a single server with infinite buffer space.
a-
Consider the situation:
The average interarrival time is 1 sec with a Poisson input process
The service time to serve each customer is always 0.5 sec
- What is the waiting time per customer?
b-
Consider the situation:
The interarrival time is exponentially distributed with a mean of a 1 sec
The service time to serve each customer is exponentially distributed with a mean of 0.5
sec
- What is the waiting time per customer?
c-
Compare the answers of a & b.
Solution:
a-
The mean arrival rate is = 1 customer/sec. The service rate is = 2 customers/sec. Using
the M/D/1 mean waiting time formula, we have:
b-
The mean arrival rate is = 1 customer/sec. The mean service rate is = 2 customers/sec.
Using the M/M/1 mean waiting time formula, we have:
c-
Waiting time is not just a function of the mean arrival and the mean service rate. It depends
on the distributions of interarrival times and service times too.
Problem 3: Repair calls are handled by one repairman at a photocopy shop. Repair time, including
travel time, is exponential distributed, with a mean rate of two hours per call. Requests for copier
repairs come in at a mean rate of three per eight-hour day (assume Poisson).
a. Determine the queueing model
M/M/1
b. Find the mean arrival rate of calls per hour = _________________________
=3/8=0.375 call per hour
c. Find the mean service rate per hour =________________________________
= 0.5 repair per hour
d. Find the average number of customers awaiting repairs.
e. Find the System utilization
f. Find the amount of time during an eight-hour day that the repairman is not out on a call.
During one our the repairman is busy 75% of the time. So he/she is not on a call 25% of
the time.
During 8 hours 8*0.25 = 2 hours
g. The probability of two or more customers in the system.
